Then the fix is in AudioCaptureKit — move the PCM writes off the processing loop's critical path. The conversion to Int16 is fast (in-memory), but the `FileHandle.write()` calls need to go to a dedicated I/O queue so the processing task can get back to draining ring buffers.

Something like:

```swift
// In CompositeCaptureSession
private let pcmWriteQueue = DispatchQueue(label: "com.pablo.audiocapture.pcm-io")

private func writeRawPCMSidecars(micSamples: [Float], systemSamples: [Float]) {
    let micPCM = stereoMixer.convertToInt16PCM(micSamples)
    let systemPCM = stereoMixer.convertToInt16PCM(systemSamples)
    pcmWriteQueue.async { [weak self] in
        self?.sessionState.withLock {
            $0.micPCMFileHandle?.write(micPCM)
            $0.systemPCMFileHandle?.write(systemPCM)
        }
    }
}
```

Processing loop converts the samples (microseconds), dispatches the write (microseconds), moves on to drain the next cycle. The disk I/O happens on its own queue and can take as long as it needs without starving the ring buffers.

Want me to make this change in AudioCaptureKit? You have the repo at `pablo-health/AudioCaptureKit`.

